How do you organize all your chargers and small electronics? Tell me in the comments! 

December has been so busy and I've been neglecting my home office. So this week (while I'm OOO 😂), I've been catching up on digital organization and cleaning up my physical office, including organizing frequently used cables and small electronics. 

This is a quick and easy project with a lot of value since it keeps things organized, labeled and easily accessible! I took a pile of cables, sorted by type, (major bonus points if you test them to ensure they work), then label the smaller bins.

I call these "Visual Victories" 
You'll see more of these examples in the future. Some on a really large scale like our renovation projects. This is a small scale example but I have so many of these visual to-do items. Some are not on a to-do list, they can come up without notice. I've literally had plants die overnight. 

When items or tasks involving your physical space, take up mental space. This can be toys on the floor, a sink full of dishes, an item laying in a common area that you walk past 20x before picking it up, dying plants, etc. 

I walk past many of these visual to do items everyday and I notice it. It takes up mental space. I used to look around at things like this with a horrible mental dialogue of "I'm failing at this... and that" 🙅🏻‍♀️
💁🏻‍♀️ I now re-frame to "this is not a priority at the moment". 

When it was a priority: I ordered new rocks, did a fun shopping trip for the plants & supported a local business. I was excited to do the project and it only took 20mins. Well 40 because I locked myself in the barn for 20 mins when I was grabbing soil 😅🤣. 

When I have felt dread, guilt or any negative feelings about projects, I make sure I take the time to celebrate and appreciate that I completed the task. This is such a beautiful visual victory! 

Now for watering adjustments to keep these healthy! 😅

Can you believe what I used to clean the counter around the sink? I’ve literally agonized over the stains for 2 years and worried I’d have to replace counters that we purchased only a few years ago. A straight blade took off the buildup with no damage to the quartz! 

I will note, our bathroom vanity is a different quartz and didn’t clean as easily (seemed like it might scratch), so do be careful if you try this as well! To prevent water stains going forward I’m using the @spaceaid_official Kitchen Sink organizer. I wipe around it regularly then with an easy lift, I can prevent water from pooling and causing buildup around the sink. 

The counter is not the only thing that can be tough to keep clean. A solid 10 mins of rinsing different angles is needed to properly get the sink basin clean, so I neglect it then use this lazy approach. I toss a dishwasher pod in with the hottest setting of water. I never touch the basin, but it comes so clean! A set it and forget it solution is my fav!

I previously kept Lego manuals in a large Lego bin, but every time Luc needed to access his Lego manuals they would all end up scattered on the floor 🤦🏻‍♀️.

Here are 2 ways you can organize those Lego manuals to help you find them fast and without the mess!

* Use the Lego app! This works great, but I try to hide the iPad unless we’re out or doing screen time games as a reward or distraction. Screen time is a tool, so any way I can have control of it…I try, lol! 😂 I went ahead & created an account and saved all the kits we have that were available in app. The small sets we often buy that come in small bags weren’t on the app, which was a bit of a bummer. Luc does those so well independently!

* I purchased a crazy amount of sheet protectors. Too cheap and they are flimsy. It was so hard to find them with the correct sizing for pages with 2 sections. I finally gave up and modified the 4 section options I found for the varying sizes of Lego manuals. I used sheet protectors meant for trading cards for the small lego manuals. For any that had a little too much wiggle room, I used double-sided tape for a non-permanent option to help them stay in place as he flips the pages.

These binders (we filled 2!) now have a home in my office and Luc loves them! He even asked to help me organize them last night since we had a few more manuals to add 🥰

Let me know if you decide to try out these tips! I’d love to see how you organize them! 🤗

Struggling with a small pantry? Here are five tips from a professional organizer to help you maximize space and keep your small pantry in order:

1. Declutter and Edit:
Start by removing everything from the pantry, and grouping items into categories. Discard expired items and donate non-perishable items you won't use. 

2. Use Clear Containers and add Labels:
Invest in transparent containers to store staples like flour, sugar, pasta, and snacks. This not only keeps your pantry looking neat but also gives you a visual to easily track inventory levels. Label each container with the item and expiration date.

3. Adjustable Shelving and Door Organizers:
Make the most of vertical space by installing adjustable shelving or use risers (like the ones pictured under the sauce basket). Additionally, utilize the back of the pantry door with door-mounted organizers for spices, sauces, or smaller items. 

4. Categorize and Group Items:
Organize items by categories to create zones within your pantry. This makes it easier to find what you need and helps maintain order over time. Consider using baskets or bins to corral like items together.

5. Implement a First In, First Out System:
Arrange items in a way that encourages you to use older items first. Place newer items at the back and older items towards the front. This helps prevent food waste by ensuring that items with shorter shelf lives are used before they expire. Regularly check your pantry for expired goods and rotate items accordingly.

Regularly reset your pantry to maintain your ideal state. Assess and update your pantry to accommodate changes in your household's needs and shopping habits.

Are you making these junk drawer mistakes? 👇 
 
1. Everything is piled in without any categorization of organization. 
 
The Fix: Implement a sorting system. Categorize items into groups such as office supplies, tools, and miscellaneous. Consider using small containers or dividers within the drawer to keep each category separate. 
 
2. The drawer is "working too hard" capturing too many categories that may not make sense for the size of the items vs the containers or drawers. 
 
The fix: Re-home categories that are outgrowing the space due to a growth in necessary items. For example, the orphan screwdriver and tape measure have now been joined by a hammer and it doesn't fit anymore. Move the category (a small toolbox under the sink, maybe?) 
 
3. Not maintaining any prior organization. 
 
The fix: Monthly sweeps to reset the space can help you avoid and hour or two overhauling your organizing systems again.

I started this habit this year and keep my Accomplishment Journal on my computer via Evernote. Only a few weeks in and I am very quick to think about it and add things. This has allowed me to go “wow, I’ve done a lot, that is a good day” vs “I didn’t complete my unrealistic, 35-item to-do list”. 

I love to add tasks that feel great to accomplish, sometimes I even add notes like “THIS FELT GOOD!” to emphasize big things that feel so good or are a relief to have completed. This has allowed me to power down in my evenings, knowing today was “enough”. I can capture, quantify, and appreciate my productivity. 

Your Action Steps: 
🗒️ Start a note on your phone or good ol’ pen and paper! 

✍🏻 Make a habit of writing things on your list as you finish them - tasks, habits, things that feel good (smooth morning routine, fun family time)

👀🎉 Review it at the end of the day and BE PROUD!
